as Jung’s most talented student. Neumann was one of the few correspondence partners of Jung’s who was able to challenge him intellectually and personally. These letters shed light on not only Jung’s political attitude toward Nazi Germany, his alleged anti-Semitism, and his psychological theory of fascism, but also his understanding of Jewish psychology and mysticism. They affirm Neumann’s importance as a leading psychologist of his time and paint a fascinating picture of the psychological impact of immigration on the German Jewish intellectuals who settled in Palestine and helped to create the state of Israel.Featuring Martin Liebscher’s authoritative introduction and annotations, this volume documents one of the most important intellectual relationships in the history of analytical psychology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJungian psychology. 0aPsychoanalysis. 0aPsychoanalystszSwitzerlandvCorrespondence. 0aPsychologistszIsraelvCorrespondence. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Jungian.2bisacsh1 aLiebscher, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiebscher, Martin.1 aMcCartney, Heather.1 aNeumann, Erich, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140086591840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400865918423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400865918.jpg  a978-3-11-066592-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK